Make a plot of total CO2 emissions over time for the U.S, China, and India. Add a few more countries of your choice. Explain what do you see.

country$totalco2 <- country$co2 + country$co2_PC
target3 <- c("United States of America", "China", "India")
country %>% 
  filter(!is.na(totalco2)) %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  filter(name %in% target3) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(time, totalco2, col=factor(name)))+
  geom_line()+
  labs(x="Time (years)", y="Total Co2 emissions", col = "Country", title="Years vs. Total Co2 Emissions")

The graph show that overtime for all countries, co2 emissions have increased for all countries. China’s growth has been the most exponential. India’s growth has also been increasing exponentially but at a slower rate. The U.S’s growth is less consistent in its pattern but it’s also generally been increasing. However in recent years the graph shows a decrease, but this could be due in part to the years of missing data.

Now let’s analyze the CO2 emissions per capita (co2_PC). Make a similar plot of the same countries. What does this figure suggest?

country %>% 
  filter(!is.na(co2_PC)) %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  filter(name %in% target3) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(time, co2_PC, col=factor(name)))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point()+
  labs(x="Time (years)", y="Co2 emissions per capita", col = "Country", title = "Co2 emissions per Capita versus years")

Per capita, the United States is far and above all other countries in emissions per capita. That said, China has increased drastically in the last decade. India’s increase has been more gradual.

Compute average CO2 emissions per capita across the continents (assume region is the same as continent). Comment what do you see. Note: just compute averages over countries and ignore the fact that countries are of different size. Hint: Americas 2016 should be 4.80.

avg_Co2_region <- country %>% 
  filter(!is.na(co2_PC), !is.na(region), !is.na(time)) %>% 
  group_by(region, time) %>% 
  summarize(avg_Co2_PC = mean(co2_PC))

Question 4

Make a scatterplot of GDP per capita versus life expectancy by country, using data for 1960. Make the point size dependent on the country size, and color those according to the continent. Feel free to adjust the plot in other ways to make it better.Comment what do you see there.

country %>% 
  filter(time == 1960, !is.na(name), !is.na(region), !is.na(GDP_PC), !is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  group_by(name, region) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x= GDP_PC, y=lifeExpectancy, col=region))+
  geom_point(aes(size=totalPopulation))+
  labs(title="GDP per capita versus life expectancy by country", x= "GDP Per Capita", y="Life Expectancy")

The graph shows that European nations have both the highest GDP and life expectancy, but European nations are the smallest in population. There doesn’t seem to be a big correlation between life expectancy + GDP and population size, otherwise the largest dots would be clustered at the top or the bottom of the data.

Make a similar plot, but this time use 2019 data only.

country %>% 
  filter(time == 2019, !is.na(name), !is.na(region), !is.na(GDP_PC), !is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  group_by(name, region) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x= GDP_PC, y=lifeExpectancy, col=region))+
  geom_point(aes(size=totalPopulation))+
  labs(title="GDP per capita versus life expectancy by country", x= "GDP Per Capita", y="Life Expectancy")

In this case, Asian nations have cot up with European nations in life expectancy, and are beginning to in terms of GDP per capita. African nations are clustered towards the lower end of both the GDP scale and life expectancy. Europe looks mostly unchanged, and the Americas seem to have moved up a bit generally in GDP.

Compare these two plots and comment what do you see. How has world developed through the last 60 years?

In general in the last 60 years the economy has accelerate in much of the world and the global supply change and global economies have become so innately intertwined. In general, by the data, it seems that countries that were ahead in GDP in 1960 are still ahead in 2019. But life expectancy seems to have topped out.

Compute the average life expectancy for each continent in 1960 and 2019. Do the results fit with what do you see on the figures? Note: here as average I mean just average over countries, ignore the fact that countries are of different size.

country %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  filter(time == 1960) %>% 
  summarize(avg_le_region = mean(lifeExpectancy, na.rm=TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(rank(desc(avg_le_region)))
## # A tibble: 6 × 2

## 2 Europe            68.3
## 3 Americas          58.6
## 4 Oceania           56.4
## 5 Asia              51.6
## 6 Africa            41.5

Yes, this does match up with the graphs. Without including the NA, Europe still has the highest average life expectancy and Africa still has the lowest life expectancy! So everything looks good so far.

Compute the average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents. Show the results in the order of growth. Explain what do you see. Hint: Hint: these data (data in long form) is not the simplest to compute growth. But you may want to check out the lag() function. And do not forget to group data by continent when using lag(), otherwise your results will be messed up!

country %>% 
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarize(growth = mean(lifeExpectancy/time, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(growth))
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   region   growth
##   <chr>     <dbl>
## 1 Europe   0.0370
## 2 <NA>     0.0369
## 3 Americas 0.0345
## 4 Oceania  0.0333
## 5 Asia     0.0326
## 6 Africa   0.0265

Much like what I explained in a previous answer, Europe’s growth rate is the highest which makes sense why they are consistently head. It’s shocking to see how low the rate is for Africa between the years, and make sense how the disparity in life expectancy has only grown with time. Otherwise, other regions aren’t too far behind in their growth rate to Europe.
